    <item>
      <title>The Quiet Power of Open-Source AI</title>
      <link>https://ikcerog.github.io/RSS-Test/articles/open-source-ai.html</link>
      <dc:creator><![CDATA[Maya Osei]]></dc:creator>
      <pubDate>Thu, 25 Jun 2026 09:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">https://ikcerog.github.io/RSS-Test/articles/open-source-ai.html</guid>
      <category>Technology</category>
      <description><![CDATA[<p>While the headlines fixate on billion-dollar labs, a decentralized community is building tools that may matter more in the long run.</p>]]></description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p>Every week brings a new announcement from one of the major AI laboratories — a model that writes code better than most engineers, a system that passes bar exams, a multimodal architecture that can reason about images with uncanny precision. The press coverage is relentless. The funding rounds are staggering. And yet, quietly, something else is happening.</p>
<p>In repositories across GitHub, in Discord servers that never make the news, in research papers published without a PR firm attached, a different kind of AI development is taking place. It is slower, messier, and more distributed. It is also, in some ways, more interesting.</p>
<h2>The Release That Changed the Conversation</h2>
<p>When Meta released the weights of LLaMA in early 2023, the effect was immediate and irreversible. Within days, the model was running on laptops. Within weeks, researchers had fine-tuned it on specialized datasets — medical records, legal documents, codebases — that the major labs would never prioritize. Within months, a whole ecosystem had formed around it.</p>
<h2>Infrastructure That Belongs to Everyone</h2>
<p>Beyond models, the open-source AI community has built infrastructure that is genuinely impressive. The Hugging Face Hub has become the repository of record for model weights, datasets, and evaluation suites.</p>
<h2>What Comes Next</h2>
<p>The open-source AI movement is at an inflection point. The models are getting genuinely competitive with proprietary alternatives. The tooling is mature enough that a small team can now build and deploy a capable AI system without relying on any of the major cloud providers.</p>
      ]]></content:encoded>
    </item>

    <item>
      <title>Why Creative Work Has Never Been Harder (or More Possible)</title>
      <link>https://ikcerog.github.io/RSS-Test/articles/creative-work.html</link>
      <dc:creator><![CDATA[Tobias Krenn]]></dc:creator>
      <pubDate>Thu, 18 Jun 2026 09:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">https://ikcerog.github.io/RSS-Test/articles/creative-work.html</guid>
      <category>Culture</category>
      <description><![CDATA[<p>The abundance of tools is real. So is the paralysis. A meditation on making things when everything can be automated.</p>]]></description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p>A friend of mine spent three months writing a short film. She had a script she was proud of, a small budget, and a cast of actors she trusted. What she did not have was the certainty, nagging and persistent, that a sufficiently clever prompt could have produced a similar draft in forty-five seconds.</p>
<h2>The Old Bargain</h2>
<p>There was an implicit bargain in the pre-automation era of creative work. You put in time. You developed taste through failure. You learned to distinguish your good ideas from your bad ones through the grueling process of executing both and living with the results.</p>
<h2>What Cannot Be Automated</h2>
<p>There is a category of creative work that AI cannot do, not for technical reasons but for conceptual ones. It cannot make work that is about the experience of making it. It cannot document a life from the inside.</p>
      ]]></content:encoded>
    </item>

    <item>
      <title>In Defense of the Slow Internet</title>
      <link>https://ikcerog.github.io/RSS-Test/articles/slow-internet.html</link>
      <dc:creator><![CDATA[Lena Vasquez]]></dc:creator>
      <pubDate>Wed, 10 Jun 2026 09:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">https://ikcerog.github.io/RSS-Test/articles/slow-internet.html</guid>
      <category>Ideas</category>
      <description><![CDATA[<p>What we lost when the web became instant, and why some designers are deliberately putting friction back in.</p>]]></description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p>There is a loading screen in a game I played as a child that I remember with a vividness I cannot explain. It was a simple animation — a spaceship moving across a star field, slowly, while a progress bar crept from left to right. It took maybe thirty seconds. I watched it every time, rapt.</p>
<h2>The Economics of Instant</h2>
<p>The elimination of latency was, for most of internet history, an unambiguous good. Waiting was waste. Users bounced. Conversion rates dropped. Every millisecond of load time had a measurable cost.</p>
<h2>The Case Against Nostalgia</h2>
<p>The case for considered friction is not a case for returning to dial-up. It is a case for being deliberate about what we optimize for, and recognizing that speed is one value among several, not a terminal goal in itself.</p>
      ]]></content:encoded>
    </item>

